<br>
I dont think this is viable for several reasons:<br>
1) if I get moved inside a zone (coth or in zone rez for instance), I wont see anything until the client gets a update.<br>
2) like you pointed out, it would up the processing that gets done on the server most likely. I bet even a 5-10% increase in this would cost soe a lot in equitpment/maintenence costs.<br>
3) would require a lot of rework to both server &amp; client code - my guess is they dont want to do this  <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
1) In zone 'teleports' or move_character requests to a distance (CotH, Succor, Rez, Decession, etc) can force an update for your client, hense seeing things as you get moved. That problem is easy to correct.<br>
<br>
2) This is probably the limiting factor. Cost for adding just one server to each world cluster could likely be prohibitive. This depends on how well they could optimize such code, doing initial bulk processing when you zone in, checking mob movement only on PC's, and similar. This, if any, is probably the reason why it isn't already this way.<br>
<br>
3) The rework isn't too bad. If you think about it, the client already knows how to discern who is in range and who isn't for visual aquisition. Move some code around to the server, and if it's not in visual range, don't send. Client can then be streamlined so that any info the server sends is gold, and to display what objects it can.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Check the Network Layer of the computer you're on. If there are any sockets running in 'raw' or promiscious mode (detectable, typically), simply refuse to start&quot;<br>
<br>
I'm not sure if thats possible to do on windows platforms. In any event, its only a fix for a sniffer on the same machine - seq could also migrate to a client-server model where the key is passed from the eqclient machine to the seq machine. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This really depends on how SoE designed the forcing to get the key from same machine. If it's in a file, why not copy the key from the file? If it's broadcast from the server (ie: down an previously encrypted link), that makes it more interesting. If they did force it onto a single machine to get the key, then the 'client' portion of SEQ might have to be in raw mode anyways, just to hear the key, hense defeating the need to have the main listener on another machine. 'sides, even if that could be doable with the fix I mentioned, then it once again becomes a 'difficult' thing to set up, and limited to a few of the technically inclined.<br>
