<br>
All programs have certain hex values associated with them, based on pure size...All programs call certain functions, and all programs take up a certain size on the HDD.<br>
<br>
If verant really wanted to, they could drop a message in their EULA, and then begin scanning the entire contents of your drive and memory, and begin doing checks against a remote database for size and CRC every time you started EQ.<br>
<br>
It would be as easy as checking the HDD for bit values, checking the RAM for matches, then requesting matches from a verant server.<br>
<br>
This would be legal...As it's not reporting anything back, it's calling to request information which would be parsed locally.. Every time you turn on the internet, this is going on.<br>
<br>
Verant could go so far as to have the remote checking process occur once you are actually in game...And if it finds a match, it cuts your stream to the server and removes your account from the database.<br>
<br>
We know verant is capable of bit checking...This is the process that goes on for autopatching. It knows when a file results in the wrong CRC. And we know it's legal, because we do it every time we START the autopatcher. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eloinapyromancer>Eloina Pyromancer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 110<br> <font color=#333333>(11/1/02 8:29:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=7687.topic&index=57>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: SEQ Declares War on VI - Show EQ for Windows availible</span><hr size=1> Sure.  And if they have a brain, you won't even know it happened.  They'll sniff the ports to see who's listening, and act accordingly.<br>
